[normal]Q1 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Welcome to our first evidence session on the performance of the Department.
[normal] 
[normal]Just for our record, if you all could just give your name and your position, that would be a good start.
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: Bob 
[normal]Kerslake
[normal], Permanent Secretary of the Department, and Head of the Civil Service.
[normal]David [bold]Rossington[bold]: David 
[normal]Rossington
[normal], Finance Director.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: Peter Schofield, Director General for Neighbourhoods.
[normal]Helen Edwards[bold]: Helen Edwards, Director General for Localism.
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: Mike Pitt of the Planning Inspectorate.
[normal]Andy Rose[bold]: Andy Rose, Chief Executive of the Homes and Communities Agency.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Thank you all for coming; you are all most welcome.
[normal] 
[normal]We understand there may be a vote on the programme motion at some point, so it is likely we are going to have to interrupt
[normal] the sitting
[normal]—
[normal]to suspend and come back again
[normal]—
[normal]but we will deal with that issue when we get to it.
[normal] 
[normal]Can we begin by looking at the focus of the Department, how it is changing, and the skills that are needed?
[normal] 
[normal]Clearly, it appears that the work the Department is doing now is much more commercially focused than it might have been a few years ago.
[normal] 
[normal]Does that need, and is it getting, a change in the skills that are available within the Department?
[normal] 
[normal]Maybe, in the future, would we assume that the Permanent Secretary might come with a commercial background?
[normal] 
[normal]Is that the sort of change we might anticipate?
[normal] 
[normal]I am not suggesting any time soon, of course.
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: Let me say first of all, Chair, that you are absolutely right to say that we are seeing a significant change in the way in which the Department works.
[normal] 
[normal]We have calculated that, by 2015, the financial instruments will constitute potentially up to £15.7
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion in terms of spend, so there is undoubtedly a shift in the Department, and it is away from predominantly 
[normal]grant
[normal]­
[normal]giving
[normal] and towards an investment model much more linked to a return on that investment, and therefore a commercial decision.
[normal] 
[normal]First of all, I think it is right to say that we are changing.
[normal] 
[normal]Secondly, have we clocked this, and are we taking it very seriously?
[normal] 
[normal]Absolutely.
[normal] 
[normal]It is clearly a priority for the whole of the team to deal with this issue.
[normal] 
[normal]Let me just give you a few examples of what we are doing here: we have developed what we call a commercial core skills programme
[normal]. 
[normal]We have now run that programme twice, first in March and then in July, and we have seen 130 on the first course and 220 on the second.
[normal] 
[normal]We are going to go beyond that and run an enhanced programme to a higher level of skills in November.
[normal] 
[normal]We have brought in commercial expertise from outside, so we have a couple of people with a background of commercial expertise.
[normal] 
[normal]We are in the process of completing a review organised with the Shareholder Executive to specifically focus on how we manage this new portfolio of investments
[normal]. 
[normal]We have quite a wide range of activity, which includes, actually, the Homes and Communities Agency taking on a strengthened role in relation to investments.
[normal] 
[normal]Just on your last point, it is perfectly conceivable that we would have a Permanent Secretary with a commercial background.
[normal] 
[normal]I have, as you know, done a number of commercial deals both in local government and in the Homes and Communities Agency, but it is also worth saying that Andy himself comes from a commercial banking background.
[normal] 
[normal]We have expertise in the Department, but, as I said earlier, a lot of expertise in the Homes and Communities Agency as well.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I will come back to the Homes and Communities Agency in just a minute.
[normal] 
[normal]Clearly, one of the biggest changes is the guarantees that the Department is going to be giving in housing, both in the social rented and private rented sector.
[normal] 
[normal]Specifically, did the Department look at the skills that would be needed to manage that, and did you bring in particular expertise to deal with that, or to re-skill people who are already there?
[normal] 
[normal]That is a massive programme, and potentially there is a major cost if it all goes wrong.
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: We have done both, in effect.
[normal] 
[normal]We have both brought in expertise to help us with some of the guarantees, and, of course, created the task force that you will be aware of in the Department.
[normal] 
[normal]We have appointed a number of 
[normal]secondees
[normal] to work on this area, and we also look to strengthen the capability of our existing staff within the Department.
[normal] 
[normal]We are doing both in relation to the guarantees, and we have also created
[normal] a credit c
[normal]ommittee, where we will establish a much stronger governance of this area in order to ensure that every decision is properly assessed for the level of risk involved.
[normal] 
[normal]You will know
[normal] that
[normal], for the affordable housing 
[normal]guarantees, we have taken on a contract in order to establish an aggregator for that work.
[normal] 
[normal]I do not know if, Peter, you
[normal] want
[normal] to add anything to that.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: Just to add to that, as Sir Bob just said, for the affordable housing guarantee scheme
[normal]—which is potentially up to half of the
[normal] £10 billion
[normal]—
[normal]we have got an agreement with Affordable Housing Finance, which is a subsidiary of the Housing Finance Corporation.
[normal] 
[normal]This is going to be acting as an aggregator, and it has been doing the first round of due diligence before proposals come forward to the credit committee.
[normal] 
[normal]The credit committee is partly staffed by existing members of staff in the Department, but we have also brought in some expertise with a banking background to sit on that credit committee.
[normal] 
[normal]The credit committee will also be there to assess proposals that come forward for the private rented guarantee scheme, so it is a combination of the two.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Just picking up on the outside expertise, recognising that salaries in the commercial sector, and particularly the finance sector, are often very much higher than they are in the public sector, are you going to have to pay more to get this expertise in?
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: So far, we have managed to make quite a lot of progress by prevailing on the banks themselves to give us secondments in to do pieces of work, so it has not cost huge amounts of additional cost to the Department.
[normal] 
[normal]Obviously, as Peter said, the advice on the credit committee will be advisory rather than necessarily full
[normal]­
[normal]time, but obviously one of the things we will have to look at
[normal], 
[normal]as we move forward and as the 
[normal]portfolio grows, 
[normal]is the nature and mix of the staff that we have.
[normal] 
[normal]What I am clear about is that whatever we do there, we will stay within our overall budget and staffing numbers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] But you could see some people get paid an awful lot more in order to attract the right people in?
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: We will clearly look at this issue of ensuring we have got the right people, and we will look at the market salaries.
[normal] 
[normal]We will aim to get people in as 
[normal]cost
[normal]­
[normal]effectively
[normal] as we can, and there is good evidence in other parts of Government, like the Shareholder Executive, that people are willing to come in to central Government, because of the nature of the work, at lower salaries that they might have commanded in the private sector.
[normal] 
[normal]That is something we will look at in more detail.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I will just turn to Mr Rose for a second.
[normal] 
[normal]Clearly, you have been mentioned in terms of the particular skills that you are bringing to the HCA.
[normal] 
[normal]Did you find a skills gap there that you needed to fill?
[normal]Andy Rose[bold]: No.
[normal] 
[normal]My first impression was actually very positive about the skills.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q7 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I suppose I might ask, then, what the point was of bringing you in.
[normal]Andy Rose[bold]: I applied for the job that was offered, because I thought it was a fascinating opportunity.
[normal] 
[normal]That was my role.
[normal] 
[normal]As I say, I am impressed with the skills.
[normal] 
[normal]I think what Sir Bob was identifying was the scale of some of these programmes, and that they have the potential to increase quite significantly: you identified the guarantee scheme.
[normal] 
[normal]My own view was that it was absolutely appropriate to ask a body like the Shareholder Executive to look at the skills sitting across the Department and the HCA to see what is required in terms of taking these programmes forward, but I think there are some very good skills in the HCA.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q8 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Heather Wheeler:[bold] I would like to ask some questions about the fact that, for the first time, you have had the accounts qualified, and you have not got an unqualified arrangement.
[normal] 
[normal]You are up there with 
[normal]Barroso
[normal], so congratulations.
[normal] 
[normal]I never thought that the Department would be in the same state as 
[normal]Europe
[normal] and the Commission.
[normal] 
[normal]It is astonishing.
[normal] 
[normal]What is your feeling of how that came about?
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: Let me say, first of all, that it was very disappointing that we had these qualifications.
[normal] 
[normal]We took the qualifications very seriously; we have conducted two internal audit reviews of the areas where we had qualifications.
[normal] 
[normal]We have looked at them in depth, and identified how and where we need to improve how we operate.
[normal] 
[normal]I would make two points, not in any sense to reduce the significance of the qualification.
[normal] 
[normal]It is worth saying first of all that there was no issue here of either spending outside budget or spending inappropriately that led to these qualifications.
[normal] 
[normal]They both related to particular forms of parliamentary control totals that we breached, and those bring with them an automatic qualification.
[normal] 
[normal]That was inevitable, but it is important to be very clear that there was no issue of either a breach in budgets or spending inappropriately.
[normal] 
[normal]I would ask David to say a few more words, if I can.
[normal] 
[normal]David [bold]Rossington[bold]: 
[normal]L
[normal]et me underline that point
[normal]: t
[normal]here were two breaches.
[normal] 
[normal]The first was to do with cash, and that was caused by not taking account of a payment that moved over from one financial year to another.
[normal] 
[normal]We were monitoring our cash right through the year, actually very well; we were very high on the 
[normal]Whitehall
[normal] league table, but we did not have the processes in place to take account of the overhang cash from the previous year.
[normal] 
[normal]As soon as we became aware of that, which was late in the year, we managed down spending so that the overall breach was £55 million rather than
[normal] what it could have been—
[normal]as high as £340 million.
[normal] 
[normal]Then, as Sir Bob has said, we immediately conducted an audit report and had a look at exactly what went wrong.
[normal] 
[normal]We have got recommendations there; they will all be implemented by the end of this month, so that we do not get a recurrence.
[normal] 
[normal]The other breach was in relation to local government 
[normal]DEL
[normal], and that was caused by two arm’s-length bodies spending more on capital than was set out in their control total.
[normal] 
[normal]Once again, there was no overspend overall in either of those agencies.
[normal] 
[normal]Once again, we immediately conducted an audit investigation of what went wrong, and there were really two things that came out of that: first of all, a need for greater awareness of 
[normal]how G
[normal]overnment accounting works in the arm’s-length bodies, and secondly, a need for better liaison between the Department and those arm’s-length bodies.
[normal] 
[normal]We are actually centralising in our finance function the arrangements for sponsoring the smaller arm’s-length bodies in the departments, again, to prevent any recurrence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q9 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Heather Wheeler:[bold] No overall overspend, two technical breaches, so nobody gets sacked?
[normal]David [bold]Rossington[bold]: There are clearly systemic problems here, and it was not a case of individuals wilfully doing things wrong.
[normal] 
[normal]The system was wrong; we have looked hard at that, and we want to put it right.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q10 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Heather Wheeler:[bold] A final thing, then: as another knock-on effect, with the retention of business rates, you are now going to be withholding £120 million from local councils, which they had not expected to be the case.
[normal] 
[normal]They would be expecting more like £50 million, or something like that.
[normal] 
[normal]It is a huge jump, and although, if it all works out all right, that money
[normal]—or what is left to it—will go back to the councils, how can
[normal] councils budget when decisions like that are being made?
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: I think you are talking about decisions that
[normal] relate to judg
[normal]ments about how much we might retain for specific initiatives like the transformation budget.
[normal] 
[normal]We have signalled them well in advance of them happening, and we have sought, wherever possible, to keep holdbacks to a minimum.
[normal]              [bold]Heather Wheeler:[bold] It is an additional £95 million holdback.
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: In the context of total funding under the 
[normal]DEL
[normal] of £25 billion, it is a relatively small amount, and we have sought to do it only where we think there is a specific need and where we want to
[normal], as I touched on, 
[normal]increase the level of funding to promote and support transformation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q11 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Heather Wheeler:[bold] With respect, it might be a small amount to you, but to district councils it is £100,000, £200,000, £300,000 or £400,000.
[normal] 
[normal]That is a huge amount of money that is being held back from them, which they were not expecting and that they have not budgeted for.
[normal]Helen Edwards[bold]: Some of the money we hold back is to help authorities.
[normal] 
[normal]For example, on business rate retention, we hold back £50 million in case local authorities do not get the rate income that they expect when an employer goes bust, or something like that.
[normal] 
[normal]Some of that is there to help people, and it does make its way back into the sector.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q12 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Heather Wheeler:[bold] But that is only after.
[normal] 
[normal]They have set 
[normal]five
[normal]­
