[normal] Okay?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q14 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]John Pugh:[bold] In 2011, the Secretary of State said, “The ERDF programme has been plagued by a legacy of poor administration and fines that dates back to 2000.
[normal] 
[normal]The Coalition Government has overhauled the management of these schemes, bringing them in-house, and successfully minimising the liabilities.”
[normal] 
[normal]Imagine our surprise when we learned in May 2013 that the European Commission has imposed payment interruption, blaming inadequate management checks and lost files.
[normal] 
[normal]Could you explain what happened, or what difficulties you met?
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: Shall I try and address that one?
[normal] 
[normal]There are two broad issues here.
[normal] 
[normal]One is to do with the level of the liabilities
[normal], which
[normal] have come down very dramatically, and Mr 
[normal]Rossington
[normal] can say more to the Committee about that in a moment.
[normal] 
[normal]In terms of the interruption, the original issues that were raised by the auditors have all been addressed, and the auditors themselves have accepted that.
[normal] 
[normal]They have now raised a new issue about the design of our systems, despite this never having been an issue in the past over the course of what is obviously a seven-year programme starting in 2007.
[normal] 
[normal]However, we are working very closely with them.
[normal] 
[normal]We are in dialogue with them on a regular basis, looking at ways to address the concerns that they have raised, and we are looking to see the interruption lifted as soon as possible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q15 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]John Pugh:[bold] Could I ask you whether you are being helped 
[normal]or 
[normal]hindered by the abolition of the RDAs here, in terms of lost expertise?
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: Let me come in on that one.
[normal] 
[normal]Actually, the systems now are more consistent across the country, more effective, more accurate and more reliable than they were before.
[normal] 
[normal]What we had before was variation
[normal]—
[normal]              [bold]Chair:[bold] Sir Bob, could I just ask you to speak up a little bit?
[normal] 
[normal]It is just a bit difficult to hear
[normal].
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: What I was saying was that what we inherited was a set of very different, varying models of handling ERDF across the RDAs, and what we have been able to do, as a consequence of it coming into the Department, is to establish a consistent approach to this.
[normal] 
[normal]That has tack
[normal]l
[normal]ed a lot of the issues.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q16 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]John Pugh:[bold] But would you say it has been a learning curve?
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: It has inevitably been a learning curve, bringing it together and establishing the common systems, and indeed some of the issues being raised by the Commission
[normal]—
[normal]I think Peter can confirm this
[normal]—
[normal]relate to issues that are still there from the previous model.
[normal] 
