[normal]              [bold]Q22 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Simon Danczuk:[bold] We have had a briefing from the National Audit Office, and they have talked about their report on the financial sustainability of local authorities.
[normal] 
[normal]You, Sir Bob, have spoken about the challenges that local authorities face.
[normal] 
[normal]Whilst they did not exactly speak about the potential for financial disaster, they did speak about things being riskier than ever before in terms of local government finances.
[normal] 
[normal]What action would you take in the event of widespread financial failure in local government, Sir Bob?
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: First of all, I think I should say that we do not think there will be widespread financial failure.
[normal] 
[normal]We have good evidence about the management of resources by local authorities that, I think, backs that view up.
[normal] 
[normal]Our view is that we are much more likely to face individual authorities where issues arise, and we have a number of tools at our disposal to help those individual authorities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q23 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Simon Danczuk:[bold] Just before you go on to those tools, to be clear, the National Audit Office said that they raised this in a particular report because
[normal]—I got the impression—
[normal]they thought it more likely than ever before that there was going to be financial failure in local authorities, and they said that it was local authorities that were raising it with them.
[normal] 
[normal]Whilst you might not think it, local authorities clearly do think it, because they have raised it with the National Audit Office.
[normal] 
[normal]They also said that it was an increase in the demand for services that was putting local authorities under more severe pressure, but tell us what the tools are that you would use if it occurs.
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: Just dealing with that point about demand, we are absolutely alive to some of the pressures on local authorities.
[normal] 
[normal]In particular, we know about the rising cost of adult care, and that is why
[normal], as you know, the Government have put £3.8 billion into funding across the health and care
[normal] sector: to seek to address some of these pressures and to change the way services operate.
[normal] 
[normal]We are acutely aware of those rising areas of demand, and we have taken action to assist local authorities in dealing with them.
[normal] 
[normal]In terms of specific authorities, we have, obviously, the accounts produced by those authorities.
[normal] 
[normal]We have the fact that local authorities are under a legal duty to produce a balanced budget.
[normal] 
[normal]We have considerable information from a range of different forms of inspectors who go to local authorities, and we have good intelligence from our localities teams, who go and talk to local authorities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q24 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Simon Danczuk:[bold] Sorry, Bob.
[normal] 
[normal]That is all about the monitoring; I understand that, but my question is what you would do in the event of widespread financial failure.
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: As I say, I do not think we believe there will be widespread financial failure.
[normal] 
[normal]We have powers to intervene in relation to specific authorities when they have difficulties, and they have
[normal]—very rarely, but have—been used.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q25 [bold]&#xa0; 
