[normal]              [bold]Q30 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]James Morris:[bold] On the point about risk management, I just wondered what role you saw the Department playing in risk management.
[normal] 
[normal]You say you are gathering a lot of data about what is happening on the ground in local authorities, but what do you perceive the role of the Department to be in risk management?
[normal] 
[normal]What do you do with the data that you collect?
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: Helen, do you want to come in on that?
[normal]Helen Edwards[bold]: Part of our role is to assess where local authorities are in terms of the reductions in income and the impact it will have on them.
[normal] 
[normal]We use the data that we get, for example, to try and skew the distribution of the grant to help those who are going to feel the effects to a large extent—so those who are particularly grant-dependent and who are not necessarily going to benefit as much from rates retention, for example.
[normal] 
[normal]We use some of the data to do that.
[normal] 
[normal]We use it in the assessment of spending power.
[normal] 
[normal]We have said that we will not allow authorities’ spending power to fall below a certain amount, so that is our way of working out everything that a council gets by way of income.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q31 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]James Morris:[bold] So you see yourself playing a very active role in risk management?
[normal] 
[normal]It is not just that it is interesting information; it will lead you to make specific interventions on local authorities.
[normal] 
[normal]Is it an interventionist role for the Department?
[normal]Helen Edwards[bold]: No, it is not, in that sense.
[normal] 
[normal]By and large, we regard it as the responsibility of local authorities to manage their own affairs and to manage them well, and, by and large, they do manage them very well.
[normal] 
[normal]However, as Sir Bob was saying, if a local authority appears to be getting into difficulty for whatever reason, there are a number of things that we can do.
[normal] 
[normal]Of course, we do work very closely with the Local Government Association, and they do a lot through their peer-led reviews and sector-led support.
[normal] 
[normal]There are a number of ways in which we try to assess what is happening with particular local authorities, and if there is a need for intervention, then we will do it in different ways.
[normal] 
[normal]By and large, it is for them to manage the risk.
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: The way I would characterise it is that local authorities want to run their own affairs, and we believe that intervention should be an absolute last resort.
[normal] 
[normal]The thing we do actively is to understand where local authorities are, where they might be running into difficulties, and where we might need to assist them in any way.
[normal] 
[normal]It is about active management of 
[normal]the information, but we would be very reluctant to intervene, unless there were compelling reasons to do so.
[normal]&#xa0;
