[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: Many of those points were made during the passage of the Growth and Infrastructure Act, as you say.
[normal] 
[normal]              [bold]Bob Blackman:[bold] I know; I made them.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: Exactly.
[normal] 
[normal]The result of that was that the Government listened to that and introduced, as you say, the neighbourhood consultation arrangements, which are a 
[normal]fast
[normal]­
[normal]track
[normal] approach that achieves all of the positive aspects of the previous regime, while also achieving the 
[normal]benefits
[normal] of a light-touch approach for what are generally the non
[normal]­
[normal]controversial types of planning applications that come into local authorities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q47 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bob Blackman:[bold] Previously, local authorities would receive a fee for a planning application for a relatively small extension.
[normal] 
[normal]They now receive nothing.
[normal] 
[normal]How have you assessed what the cost will be to local authorities of doing this work, where they are going to be doing it for nothing, as opposed to getting some form of fee, which, I accept, was not necessarily covering the cost of doing it?
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: Our analysis took into account the fact that by stripping out a large number of applications that were previously received—
[normal]Bob Blackman:[bold] But they all have to be notified to the local authority, and then the local authority have to ask the neighbours whether they object.
[normal] 
[normal]That is no different 
[normal]from
[normal] the consultation process that used to take place, effectively.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: The next stage of the operation is much, much reduced.
[normal] 
[normal]To give you an example, in the London Borough of Enfield, they tell us that between May and August, when they gave us these numbers, they had received something like 67 notifications and only something like seven objections in total.
[normal] 
[normal]Although there will be some objections, the numbers we are talking about are significantly lower than the process that you would have to have done routinely under the old regime.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q48 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bob Blackman:[bold] 
[normal]I
[normal]t could be that the local authorities are not consulting properly, which is another consideration.
