[normal]Q95 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] We heard some evidence about risk management and modelling in earlier questions.
[normal] 
[normal]I want to ask about the risk management modelling that was done before Help to Buy was introduced, and specifically the 20% significantly 
[normal]interest
[normal]­
[normal]free
[normal] loan that the Government is giving on the first part.
[normal] 
[normal]What modelling was done, and what assumption was made, about the future direction of house prices, given that house prices have historically been very difficult to predict?
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: The Help to Buy equity loan scheme was introduced off the back of the previous First Buy scheme, which equally offered an equity loan.
[normal] 
[normal]I would argue that it is not a free loan; it is an equity loan, so the value of the loan appreciates in line with the value of the property.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q96 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] That is the critical point: what happens in respect of new properties?
[normal] 
[normal]Many new properties are sold, and immediately they are worth 5% less than the purchase price, so what would happen if somebody were to redeem their Help to Buy loan very early on 
[normal]on
[normal] a new property?
[normal] 
[normal]Would that not involve some form of loss to the Government?
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: Not in that case, of course, because a Help to Buy equity loan requires a 5% deposit by the borrower.
[normal] 
[normal]I would also add on that that what we have seen coming into the housing market is an increase in confidence, some increase in transactions, and small increases in prices, and what we are seeing is Help to Buy being one of the factors that is helping to provide greater confidence into the housing market.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q97 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] Going back to my original question, then, what change in house prices did you allow for in your modelling when you brought the proposal forward?
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: We looked at a range of modelling, with house prices staying constant or, indeed, going up.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q98 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] What does your model tell you about house prices over the next five years?
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: The point that Peter is making is that we did not make an assumption about where prices would go: what we did was a sensitivity analysis, to look at what would happen in terms of our investments if they went up and what would happen if they went down.
[normal] 
[normal]That analysis then formed part of the risk assessment, which in turn addressed the issue of what we would need to cover within our budgets to cover any potential losses.
[normal] 
[normal]It was not about the question of predictions on house prices.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q99 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] By how much would house prices need to rise for there to be no loss at all to the Government from the scheme?
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: As I say, remember that the scheme requires the borrower to put down a deposit of 5%, and that is the thing that takes the first hit in any price reduction.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q100 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] Why, in that case, is the Scrutiny Unit of the House of Commons saying that—and I quote—“the Government is relying on house prices of new-build properties included in the scheme rising by two thirds over 25 years (2% per year) to cover its own borrowing costs?”
[normal] 
[normal]Do you disagree with that?
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: I have not seen that particular report.
[normal] 
[normal]I would have to look at that to understand what the assumptions are that they are making, but all I would say, Mr 
[normal]Pawsey
[normal], is that given the 
[normal]structure of the way that the Help to Buy equity loan scheme works, house prices would have to fall in the case of any individual loan for the Government to take a loss.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q101 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] Can I put it to you that one of the criticisms of Help to Buy, and particularly the mortgage guarantee scheme coming forward now, is that we are going to get a very significant rise in house prices over the coming years, so those who have concerns about losses to the Government in the short term are misguided
[normal]? 
[normal]Do you accept that there might be a bubble, and that prices could rise very quickly over the next year or two?
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: I do not accept that there is a bubble, for a number of very clear reasons.
[normal] 
[normal]When you look at what is happening in terms of the number of transactions in the property market at the moment, we are still a considerable way down from where we were back in 2005, and certainly back from where we were in 2007.
[normal] 
[normal]Likewise, mortgage approvals are something like half of where they were in 2007 at the moment.
[normal] 
[normal]What we are seeing—very much as the Ernst &amp; Young ITEM Club report suggested this morning—is a scheme that is targeted and well-timed.
[normal] 
[normal]That is the equity loan scheme, which has been in place, as you say, since April.
[normal] 
[normal]The mortgage guarantee scheme, which you also referred to in your question, is introduced in January.
[normal] 
[normal]I think the Chancellor has been very clear in what he has said about the way in which there will be a role for the Bank of England going forward, on an annual basis, to assess what is happening in terms of demand.
[normal] 
[normal]As I say, where we currently stand, there would be a long way to go before we get anywhere near where we were, for example, in 2007.
[normal] 
[normal]In the event that we do, the Bank of England have a role in advising the Chancellor about criteria in terms of who could be eligible.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q102 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] In terms of your modelling of both parts of the scheme, how many new homes do you expect each part to deliver?
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: I can speak for the equity loan scheme, which is the one that we are responsible for.
[normal] 
[normal]What we have talked about is providing funding for around about 75,000 new homes over the course of the three years.
[normal] 
[normal]I am delighted to say that so far, in the first six months, we have seen 15,000 reservations, so we are on track for quite a considerable uptake and a considerable contribution to new supply.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q103 [bold]&#xa0; 
