[normal] 
[normal]We currently have 81 plans under examination within the Planning Inspectorate.
[normal] 
[normal]Not all of those are core strategies; some of them are area action plans and so on, and we know that there are another 68 plans in the pipeline, coming towards us at the moment.
[normal] 
[normal]There seems to be a 
[normal]speeding
[normal]­
[normal]up
[normal] of local planning at the local planning authority end.
[normal] 
[normal]The other thing I would just like to add is that the LGA, the Planning Inspectorate and DCLG have invested a great deal of energy in working with individual local authorities and the groups of local authorities to give them as much advice as we possibly can to help speed along the local planning process.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q129 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] But there remain some authorities who would rather be slow about getting a local plan, be reluctant to allocate the resources to 
[normal]plan
[normal]­
[normal]making
[normal] rather than development 
[normal]control, wait for the applications to come in, turn them down, and then blame you.
[normal] 
[normal]What steps are you able to take to encourage local authorities to put more resource into 
[normal]plan
[normal]­
[normal]making
[normal]?
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: It is by a process of encouragement.
[normal] 
[normal]Many statements have been made by Ministers and civil servants about the importance of local planning; in fact, the whole national planning system depends on having local plans in place as far as possible.
[normal] 
[normal]I am very strongly in favour of local authorities getting on with this work and making it a priority.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q130 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] In terms of the new system, the core level is neighbourhood plans, and I am very pleased that I have a neighbourhood front-runner in my constituency that I pay lots of attention to.
[normal] 
[normal]Can I say that they were absolutely horrified when they got stuck into the process and discovered very substantial amounts of bureaucracy and a great deal of power with the local authority?
[normal] 
[normal]As the process moves forward, how can we make it easier for neighbourhoods to get on with their neighbourhood plan without feeling that it is going to be very bureaucratic and they are constantly going to have to be looking over their 
[normal]shoulder at the local authority?
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: Again, I wonder whether Peter would want to come in on that.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: There has been a lot of innovation in the way that we have supported neighbourhood planning.
[normal] 
[normal]We have got something like 500 communities up and down the land who are producing neighbourhood plans.
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] Still only one per constituency, if we have got 500.
[normal] 
[normal]That is not very many.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: I had not thought about it that way.
[normal] 
[normal]That is true, but there are some parts of the country where there is more intense activity than others.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q131 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] So that means that there are some parts of the cou
[normal]ntry where nothing is happening.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: And there are some parts of the country where there is an awful lot happening.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q132 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] The question is about how we make it easier in those parts of the country where there is not so much happening, where it is perceived to be bureaucratic, and the local authority is going to be constantly looking over their shoulder.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: There are a number of different things that we can do.
[normal] 
[normal]One is the engagement with those communities to help them address barriers, if they exist, and there has been a wonderful approach in terms of the network of social media that has been used in order to reach out and build those communities and, actually, get quite a lot of cross-sharing going on amongst them.
[normal] 
[normal]The Department funds quite a lot of advice to those groups, as well, and incentives, through the way that 
[normal]C
[normal]IL works, in order to encourage local authorities to take this very seriously.
[normal]Sir Bob [bold]Kerslake[bold]: I think it is just worth adding that we now have some that have gone through the complete process, including the referendum, and they are terrifically strong examples that it is possible to do this.
[normal]              
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] Certainly, the front-runner in my constituency has been very appreciative of the support provided by RTPI in planning aid.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q133 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Sir Michael, one of the issues around local plans is not merely getting them in place—and there is sometimes a temptation for authorities to sit back and think, “Oh, that has been 
[normal]a hard job; we do not have to do it again for another 10 years”—but actually keeping them up to date.
[normal] 
[normal]Do you think the systems are really in place to allow that sort of light-touch revision on an ongoing basis, which is really needed if plans are going to be realistic and relevant?
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: Indeed.
[normal] It is a combination
[normal] of getting those local authorities that have never had an adopted plan moving as quickly as possible to have one, and also keeping an eye on the ones that were adopted quite some time ago to keep them u
[normal]p to date, because the data do
[normal] move on.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q134 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Is the system there flexible enough to allow that to happen in an easy way?
[normal] 
[normal]Local authorities do not 
[normal]often 
[normal]tend to do that, seemingly.
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: There is a statutory process that they have to go through, which includes, of course, consultation and all the analysis that is required.
[normal] 
[normal]I do not think there is any way that you could amend a local plan easily without taking into account the work that would have to be done by the officers of the local authority concerned.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: Just to add to that, it is possible just to address a small number of policies.
[normal] 
[normal]Rather than completely re-opening the plan, what you can do is focus that work on one or two policies.
[normal]              
[normal]Chair:[bold] Like the five-year housing supply update.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: Yes.
[normal] 
[normal]If there are just one or two things that need to be updated in light of evidence that has come in, then there are, as Sir Michael says, some fast-track ways of doing that that do not require you to completely redo a plan from scratch.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q135 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Heather Wheeler:[bold] 
[normal]I am asking this
[normal] question because I ge
[normal]nuinely do not know the answer. I
[normal]n the old days, when one had emerging local plans, if there was a planning application that came in, even though the old plan was redundant or whatever, inspectors would deal with it on the basis of the emerging local plan.
[normal] 
[normal]When district councils are putting a huge amount of effort and cost into re-consulting for the third time—and this will be the final consultation—that is practically it: that is the emerging local plan, and we are still seeing lots of speculative planning applications coming in.
[normal] 
[normal]There does not seem to be the feel that they can be fought off, because the emerging local plan is so close.
[normal] 
[normal]How do you feel your inspectors are coping with that?
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: The inspectors are required to give an appropriate amount of weight to an emerging local plan, and that depends on what stage it has got to.
[normal] 
[normal]At the very initial stages, then very little weight at all would be attached to it.
[normal] 
[normal]If it is extremely close to adoption, it becomes quite a powerful document, and it is a matter for the inspector in each individual case to make a judgement about how much weight to attach to that emerging local plan.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q136 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Heather Wheeler:[bold] Councils have been given that nod, have they?
[normal] 
[normal]I do not know that they are hearing it.
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: No, I think that has been the standard practice for many years, and it is well understood that that is the way things are done by the inspectorate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q137 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Heather Wheeler:[bold] So why are planning officers saying, “We cannot fight this off”?
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: As I say, it will depend on the status of their particular draft plan.
[normal] 
[normal]Clearly, it is in a much better place if it has already been adopted by the local authority, in which case it then becomes the major determinant of the outcome of the appeal.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q138 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bob Blackman:[bold] Turning to planning call-ins, the changes from the last Government to this Government, and over the last three years, have seen quite a considerable reduction in the number of call-ins by Ministers.
[normal] 
[normal]What are the criteria now being applied for a planning call-in?
[normal] 
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: The criteria were 
[normal]set out in a written m
[normal]inisterial statement in October of last year, and I would refer the Committee to that.
[normal] 
[normal]Somewhere in my briefing pack, I have that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q139 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bob Blackman:[bold] Have they not changed since then?
[normal] 
[normal]Obviously, there has been quite a drop this year in terms of the number of call-ins.
[normal]Peter Schofield[bold]: As I say, the call-in criteria were revised in October last year, and they have not changed since.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q140 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bob Blackman:[bold] Sir Michael, what effect has the drop in the number of call-ins had on your department?
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: In the case of a call-in, which is a decision by the Secretary of State, it is then referred to a planning inspector, who will examine the evidence for and against and make a recommendation to the Secretary of State.
[normal] 
[normal]What we look at is a balanced portfolio of workload.
[normal] 
[normal]It always seems to me that as one goes down, another one is going up, and by and large, we try and get our resources as close as we possibly can to meet the requirement.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q141 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bob Blackman:[bold] So the reduction in call-ins has enabled you to speed up work elsewhere?
[normal] 
[normal]What has been the effect?
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: That is right.
[normal] 
[normal]There is always a backlog of appeals, so we re
[normal]­
[normal]allocate inspectors and staff on
[normal] to those appeals
[normal] and speed them up as quickly as we can.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q142 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bob Blackman:[bold] I do not know the answer to this: has the appeals process speeded up considerably?
[normal] 
[normal]Can we look at statistics that show that you are performing much better?
[normal] 
[normal]What is happening?
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: The appeals process will be speeding up quite dramatically from 1 October, arising from the planning reform process, where we are being set much tighter targets for dealing with written representations, hearings, and public inquiries.
[normal] 
[normal]I do hope, in a year’s time, my successor will be able to report to you that there has been a dramatic improvement in the speed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q143 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bob Blackman:[bold] One final question, then, on written appeals: is the determination of a written appeal made by the inspector now, or is that on consideration of both the appellant and objectors?
[normal]Sir Michael Pitt[bold]: It does not really matter whether it is by written representation, hearing, or public inquiry as to the outcome.
[normal] 
[normal]It is just that as a case gets more complex, then a hearing or a public inquiry becomes more appropriate.
[normal] 
[normal]But the decision on a transferred appeal is made by the inspector weighing up the evidence for and against, and, of course, the inspector can ask further questions if he or she is not satisfied that there is sufficient evidence to make a choice.
[normal]              [bold]              [bold]Chair:[bold] Thank you all very much for coming to give evidence this afternoon.
